{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15448"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69810"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8139"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55266"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"10956"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19729"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69810"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to her GP with a six-month history of bloody diarrhoea, abdominal pain and weight loss. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft with mild tenderness in the left lower quadrant. Colonoscopy with biopsy is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological process that leads to branching crypts in colonic mucosa?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Architectural distortion from chronic inflammation and repair","Acute inflammatory cell infiltrate with crypt abscesses","Increased intraepithelial lymphocytes","Submucosal fibrosis with muscle hypertrophy","Granuloma formation with giant cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBranching crypts are an important histological feature seen in inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), particularly in ulcerative colitis. \u003Cstrong\u003EArchitectural distortion from chronic inflammation and repair\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes the pathological process leading to branching crypts. This occurs due to repeated cycles of mucosal injury and healing, resulting in irregular and branched crypts that deviate from their normal parallel arrangement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute inflammatory cell infiltrate with crypt abscesses\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in both IBD and acute self-limited colitis. While these changes may coexist with branching crypts, they do not explain the mechanism of crypt branching itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranuloma formation with giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature of Crohn disease but is not directly related to the formation of branching crypts. Granulomas are discrete collections of epithelioid histiocytes, sometimes with giant cells, that can occur throughout the bowel wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased intraepithelial lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic finding in coeliac disease and microscopic colitis, not typically associated with branching crypts. This feature represents a different type of inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubmucosal fibrosis with muscle hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E can occur as a consequence of chronic inflammation in IBD but does not explain the development of branching crypts, which is a mucosal phenomenon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of branching crypts is an important diagnostic feature that helps differentiate chronic IBD from acute self-limited colitis. This architectural distortion typically requires at least 2-3 weeks to develop and persists even during periods of quiescent disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Branching crypts in colonic mucosa are a histological hallmark of inflammatory bowel disease, particularly in chronic ulcerative colitis.","Crypt architectural distortion with branching occurs due to repeated cycles of inflammation and repair.","The presence of branching crypts helps differentiate inflammatory bowel disease from acute self-limited colitis."],"references":["Rubio CA, Schmidt PT, Lang-Schwarz C, Vieth M. Branching crypts in inflammatory bowel disease revisited. J Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2022 Mar;37(3):440-445. doi: 10.1111/jgh.15734. Epub 2021 Nov 17. PMID: 34750862.","Lang-Schwarz C, Rubio CA, Vieth M. Diagnostic Impact of Crypt Branching in Patients With Crohn\u0027s Disease: A Validation Study. Anticancer Res. 2022 Apr;42(4):1919-1923. doi: 10.21873/anticanres.15669. PMID: 35347011.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55266"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55266"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:52:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T21:37:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8139"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"